  "prompt": "What type of order should I place for a stock that is expected in to increase sharply?",
  "response": "If you expect a stock to increase sharply, you would typically place a \"Buy\" order. There are several types of buy orders you can use depending on your specific strategy:\n\n1. Market Order: Buys the stock at the current market price\n- Fastest execution\n- No guarantee of specific price\n- Good for stocks with high liquidity\n\n2. Limit Order: Buys the stock only at or below a specified price\n- More control over purchase price\n- May not execute if price doesn't reach your limit\n- Protects against paying too much\n\n3. Stop Order (Buy Stop): Triggers a buy when stock reaches a price above current market price\n- Useful for momentum trading\n- Helps capture upward price movement\n- Ensures you buy when stock starts rising\n\nEach order type has pros and cons, so choose based on:\n- Your risk tolerance\n- Trading strategy\n- Stock's trading characteristics\n- Market conditions\n\nI recommend consulting a financial advisor or doing thorough research before making investment decisions.",
